<span id="freeTextContainer16261528517392806970">I just love this story â€“ it is my all-time favorite of Poeâ€™s works. This probably has something to do with the tender age at which I first read it (and the creep factor it engendered in me), but I still consider it my favorite and extremely creepy!<br/><br/>Poe, like Ray Bradbury (another favorite of mine), lets the readerâ€™s imagination fill in the blanks. Yet, even while allowing the readerâ€™s creative vision to complete the picture, I love the details of the setting that Poe gives in this story. I can pi</span>
  <span id="freeText16261528517392806970" style="display:none">I just love this story â€“ it is my all-time favorite of Poeâ€™s works. This probably has something to do with the tender age at which I first read it (and the creep factor it engendered in me), but I still consider it my favorite and extremely creepy!<br /><br />Poe, like Ray Bradbury (another favorite of mine), lets the readerâ€™s imagination fill in the blanks. Yet, even while allowing the readerâ€™s creative vision to complete the picture, I love the details of the setting that Poe gives in this story. I can picture the costumes, the party, the character of the unfortunate Fortunado, and the catacombs that house the wine cellar. As Montresor leads Fortunado deeper and deeper into the cellar, simply through the use of language, the chill beneath the skin on my arms begins to build.<br /><br />And the ending, whoa. That it didnâ€™t give me nightmares when I read it as a child is amazing (although there is absolutely nothing graphic included â€“ which I suppose answers that question), as the visions/sounds/surroundings brought to mind by the ending are still chilling to me now. Absolutely wonderful! Especially to a person who doesnâ€™t care for gory or explicit horror. Instead, this story elicits dread which, to my mind, is as close as I want to get to true horror.<br /><br />Highly recommended!</span>
